NY’s is the time to revisit, sometimes, to pleasantly rediscover, relearn from your own ever-evolving self, ( some of my videos go back to when I was 15 years old), and, most importantly, it is the moment to thank wholeheartedly our musical colleagues, who I’m feeling truly grateful to.
To me, a musical journey  in a form of rehearsals, concerts, recordings and what comes in-between, could take partners-in-music through a rollercoaster of the old -fashioned graciousness that requires the stamina of a flagship captain and an University degree in diplomacy. 
Also, when based on mutual respect, it creates an invisible pact of loyalty and a special place in your heart that lasts a lifetime, no matter the circumstances that could occur along the way.

Here’s  looking back at my YouTube channels’ videos.
My NY’s resolution, promise, is going to be to finally look at both of my existing YouTube channels and videos and, with lots of luck and the enthusiastic input from you, to create! 
The core moving force and the reason to creating more video content would be solely you. Because you’re my audience!
Cheers !

💐 the blitz-trip to the Teatro di San Carlo 🎭 the old-fashion proverb says that theater starts with a hanger. 
Of course, this statement doesn’t fit at all, as theater today sometimes starts with a late train, searching for an open lunch place through the intense contact with the street crowds cheerfully wandering around under the balconies filled with fresh laundry or along the stately palazzi, the welcoming warmth of a restaurant owner who doesn’t leave you unless you’re fed really well, ready to embrace, impossible time to even think of getting a slice from a famous pizza place or an ice cream on the busy theater square while you’re joining others into the theater doors. 
  Splendid, physically beautiful location of the city, the world of its own, the historical theater is still extremely well attended and is, admirably, the matter of pride for so many fans.
 Compliments to the artists, who performed the roles in the Wagner’s Die Walkure, The Valkyries, filling up the auditorium with the drawn out Wagnerian melodic dynamic rage and phrasing,additionally so, against the spartan primitivist stage backdrop.

Making a recording is a journey. It starts with a dream based on the foundation of years and experience as long as the decades. 

This takes you through the spector of emotions and self- evaluation, from the moment of reassessment of thoughts, hours and days going through the scores in your own music library and rehearsing the music behind the closed doors, when no one can hear it. 

Taking the full responsibility for your own thoughts, -only then you can convey to all, all of us, and firstly, to yourself.

To achieve the meaningfulness of a recording album that you yourself would come back to listen to as an artist, is always an investment, it is the priority in a stretch of several years of your life in the course of the production.

While it all seems to be done reasonably quickly, taking time, coming back to listen to it with the fresh layout of thoughts in your mind, often, with a new perspective, with a new wisdom, is the proven way, it is a must.

Then, comes the rest. The highs. The lows. The incredible. The exhaustion. The time. Pandemic. The vision. The differences of the artistic views between an artist and a sound engineer, who is an artist of his own, for several perspectives to reach the golden point. Because making a recording is an art.
.

My look might remind you of an old western outfit- this is the shirt , as a cotton eyelet skirt and a blouse, I was wearing for my graduation night at the Central Music school in Moscow, Soviet Union, - the country that was worse than North Korea. 
Wearing white dresses used to be a tradition for young women from noble families in tsarist Russia, the tradition has ceased to exist over a 100 years ago since Bolsheviks brought the country to total distraction.
Not thinking about it, I happened to be the only girl who was dressed in white that day. I received a compliment from the lady who was one of our Music History teachers. She was surprised to see me clad in white. 🤍

My NEW INTERVIEW is out now!
“ With her stunning album Solo Cello, cellist Nina Kotova exhibits these qualities in abundance. Baroque works by Bach, Handel, and the viol virtuoso Marin Marais engage in rich dialogue with 20th-century tours de force by Casals' student Gaspar Cassadó, plus Hindemith and Schnittke. We asked the artist about the album, made with Delos—an American label marking its first half-century in 2023.
---------------------------
ArkivMusic: You have released albums with several labels since your self-titled debut record in 1999, but since 2002, you have returned periodically to Delos. How did your work with the label begin, and what brought you back for your Tchaikovsky album and for this release, Solo Cello?
 
Nina Kotova: These three recordings are highlights of my recording career. Delos gave me the opportunity and the freedom I needed to choose the repertoire I really love to play and always dreamed of recording.

The recording Nina Kotova Plays Tchaikovsky represents a milestone of my recording career. The Rococo Variations are one of the most important works for cello and orchestra. It has been with me since day one, and I listened to the recordings and performances of this work since I was a very young student. The music of Tchaikovsky is where the foundation of a Slavic soul lays.
 
Solo Cello was recorded in the middle of the pandemic. I immediately thought to release it on Delos, and I was very happy when I found out Delos was just as enthusiastic about the project. The recording is a personal project: just the cello, you, the chair, and silence. It brings back to me many thoughts, recollections of people and warm memories of working with my teachers. I vividly remember meeting Alfred Schnittke in Moscow. After graduating from the Musik Hochschule in Cologne, when I first played this special piece, the score was given to me by my former professor Boris Pergamenchikov. I still have the score which was hand-written on paper by the composer himself.”
